President Biden and President Lula of Brazil met in New York to discuss their shared commitment to leaving a better world for future generations. They discussed their collaboration on tackling the climate crisis, promoting inclusive economic growth, and standing up for human rights. They also expressed their intention to launch a new Partnership for Workers' Rights. President Lula praised President Biden's advocacy for workers' rights and expressed the importance of working together to offer decent jobs and hope to working families. They discussed the potential for collaboration on the energy transition, including investments in renewable energy sources. Both leaders emphasized the importance of reducing poverty and inequality for the benefit of all. They expressed their commitment to building a better world through solidarity and fairness. President Lula highlighted the social inclusion policies implemented in Brazil and their efforts to improve the lives of their people. President Biden acknowledged the benefits of organized labor and eradicating poverty for the entire economy. They concluded the meeting and moved on to discuss business matters.